Your name and your deeds were forgotten
Before your bones were dry,
And the lie that slew you is buried
Under a deeper lie;

But the thing that I saw in your face
No power can disinherit:
No bomb that ever burst
Shatters the crystal spirit.

Between the shadow and the ghost,
Between the white and the red,
Between the bullet and the lie,
Where would hide your head?

For where is Manuel Gonzalez,
And where is Pedro Aguilar,
And where is Ramon Fenellosa?
The earthworms know where they are.

The treacherous guns had told their tale
And we both had bought it,
But my gold brick was made of gold ‚Äì
Oh! who ever would have thought it?

Good luck go with you, Italian soldier!
But luck is not for the brave;
What would the world give back to you?
Always less than you gave.

But oh! what peace I knew then
In gazing on his battered face
Purer than any woman‚Äôs!

For the flyblown words that make me spew
Still in his ears were holy,
And he was born knowing that I had learned
Out of books and slowly.

For #worldpoetryday Orwell's poem Spanish Civil War poem has never felt more relevant, it is right now. 

The Italian soldier shook my hand
Beside the guard-room table;
The strong hand and the subtle hand
Whose palms are only able

To meet within the sounds of guns,

These images are from the @NAM_London and its series of Virtual Exhibitions. There are several looking at the roles of women in and before WW2. https://t.co/drXWGS2YKR
Obviously also famous for the then Princess Elizabeth doing her bit for the war effort in the ATS. #VEDay75 https://t.co/vgFxnncGhR

By the end of the Second World War, around 250,000 women had served in the ATS. The skills they had picked up along the way were coveted by new and expanding industries in post-war civilian society, including banking and the newly founded @NHS.  #VEDay75 https://t.co/nMJmt4h2Se

The ATS also included women from across the Empire. Around 5,000 members of the ATS served in the Middle East, and about 300 women from the West Indies served in the ATS.#VEDay75 https://t.co/UWcoztCV5F

There were other bizarre differences for the ATS. When men stood on guard all night they had their rifle, when the ATS stood on guard we had a broom handle, but that did change. #VEDay75 https://t.co/gygQRTxjlh

No surprise that despite their vital contribution, ATS women were not treated the same as men. On average they received two-thirds the pay of male soldiers of similar rank. They also received 20 per cent less rations. #VEDay75 https://t.co/pGMwNcEmxM
Although women in the ATS couldn‚Äôt fight they did run anti-aircraft, sound detectors while others operated searchlights and radar equipment. #VEDay75 https://t.co/tYYjOTTd9i

Women serving in the ATS would find themselves for the first time working as car mechanics, drivers, despatch riders, mess orderlies, postal workers, ammunition inspectors and military police. #VEDay75 https://t.co/w3OUfWNKox

Originally created in 1938 as volunteers, the National Service Act made the conscription of women legal. Initially, only single women aged 20-30 were called up, mostly as cooks, bakers, clerks and storekeepers, but the jobs the ATS did expanded. #VEDay75 https://t.co/T4WtYrKFa2
The ‚Äòblonde bombshell‚Äô was part of a series of posters Games did for the ATS that also includes these two. #VEDay75 https://t.co/BY5ULInPst

One is a recruitment poster created in 1941, by the designer Abram Games. Nicknamed the 'blonde bombshell', the poster was controversial but very successful. You can check these out at the @NAM_London, which is running a Virtual #VEDay75 exhibition. #VEDay75 https://t.co/NrQ1cvzKSz

For #VEDay75 thinking my grandmother (that‚Äôs her) who served in the women‚Äôs branch of the army, the Auxiliary Territorial Service along with 250,000 women during the war whose contribution is sometimes overlooked. The ATS is famous for a couple of things. https://t.co/PiDTwohMYz
